text:
i just wanted to share some amazing news! you may or may not have heard about my documentary, but we are pretty excited about how well its doing on the festival circuit!! "documentary about akronâ€™s own angie haze is enjoying success in festivals around the world!" akron, oh - filmmaker todd v has spent the last 3 years working closely and documenting the life of akron based singer-songwriter angie haze. out of that process he has created a very special film that chronicles not only angieâ€™s creative process, but also the reasons behind her work. angie haze may not yet be a household name, but in her hometown, and in fact, regionally, she has made quite a name for herself in the music industry. as a multi award winning songwriter and stunning performer, she has become a perennial favorite of listeners of the summit.

this documentary digs a bit deeper into her life and creative process. in this era of the #metoo movement, we have seen how difficult yet important it is for people to speak out about their abuse, which in turn encourages other survivors to feel empowered to do the same. in this film, angie shares her own story of abuse and how it shaped the artist that she is today. it is heart wrenching and yet inspiring to see angie open up and confront her past, and create music to both aid in her healing and that of her fans. 
the film has only been on the festival circuit for a short time but has already gotten these awards:

winner - film on women - cult critic movie awards (india)
finalist - aprhodite film awards (nyc, usa)
official selection - award in inspirational films -  wrpn.tv short, tight and loose global film festival competition (delaware, usa)
official selection - garâ€™s garasjens film festival (norway)
official selection - wrpn women's international film festival (delaware, usa). #documentary #film #musicfilms #music #theangiehazeproject
name: The Angie Haze Project

una meta a veces difÃ­cil de sostener.
te cuento que cuando a mi me pasÃ³, las que habÃ­an sido mis amigas "de la infancia", "del colegio", no me creyeron. 
no me lo dijeron en la cara, pero una de ellas, con hijos, incluso, uno de esos hijos es mujer y ya casi mayor de edad por entonces. esa mujer no sorora, lo hablÃ³ en una reuniÃ³n de esas de "reencuentro escolar", a la que yo no habÃ­a ido. estÃ¡ ex amiguita dijo: "seguro que es mentira, debe ser con alguien que saliÃ³ y se enojÃ³" ... mis amigas no preguntaron. tampoco se acercaron a mi, como si contagiara, ni me preguntaron nada. 
los chicos, sÃ­, los hombres compaÃ±eros de infancia se acercaron. 
por otro lado, gente curiosa, que preguntaban la parte del morbo, de los detalles. Â¿para quÃ©?  si no eran ni abogad@s ni iban a salir en mi defensa...
pasÃ© de ell@s... caÃ­ en algunas "profesionales de la salud" como una psicÃ³loga que me grabÃ³ el audio de la sesiÃ³n con lujo de detalles ... y cuando se lo pedÃ­ para el juicio no  me lo quiso dar.

una guionista que lo Ãºnico que pretendÃ­a era tener datos para escribir al respecto, quizÃ¡s con realismo.

primero me contaron lo que una de ellas habÃ­a dicho,dos de los chicos y despuÃ©s,un aÃ±o despuÃ©s  se acercaron 3 mujeres de diferentes edades pidiÃ©ndome  perdÃ³n por haberles creÃ­do a Ã©sta hoy ex amiga a-sorora
que feo, triste y fuerte, ademÃ¡s de lo que te pasÃ³...tener que escuchar esos agravios.
esta ilustraciÃ³n, representa mi deseo Ã©ste #2019.
 el caso mÃ­o, sucediÃ³ en #2015 y Ã©ramos 3 mujeres abrazadas. mi madre, ceci (madre de mis sobrinos nietos) y yo.

en #2018 fuimos mÃ¡s. pero aÃºn se critican  entre mujeres...minas que hablan de "lo pura que es tal o cual". deseo que nos multipliquemos en amor, verdad y sonrisas + sanaciÃ³n comunitaria.

peace.

goodmorning saints! god says: come out of your tomb! lazarus was dead in his tomb but jesus saw fit to resurrect him from the dead! a lot of us need to be resurrected from time to time because of the things going on in our lives. a big part of being resurrected is being unbound from our emotional state of being. first thing we have to do is answer the call from jesus to come out of our tombs! the bible says: â€œwhen he had said these things, he cried out with a loud voice, â€œlazarus, come out." the man who had died came out, his hands and feet bound with linen strips, and his face wrapped with a cloth. jesus said to them, â€œunbind him, and let him go.â€ johnâ€¬ â€­11:43-44â€¬ â€­esvâ€¬â€¬. jesus called to lazarus and told him to come out and he walked out! remember jesus will call but it's up to you to come out! and once you come out jesus will unbind you! letting go of pain, hurt and anger with forgiveness in your heart is key once you are out of your tomb! the bible also says: "let all bitterness and wrath and anger and clamor and slander be put away from you, along with all malice. be kind to one another, tenderhearted, forgiving one another, as god in christ forgave you. â€ephesiansâ€¬ â€­4:31-32â€¬ â€­esvâ€¬â€¬. also remember the things that are binding you can cause you to sin! so answer the call! come out of your tomb! and allow god to free you from bondage! amen!! i love you all with the love of jesus christ! stay blessed and faithful!

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
the death of a lie #113 - victim shaming will continue to silence women & girls. statements like if you really got raped you would have...... are insensitive, inhumane and detached.  although every situation is different rape is not different,  it is rape. especially to the person who experienced it. 
deciding someone's value based on their clothing, body type, sexual history, personality or age is the very thing that allows women to continue to be preyed upon.  these ideals continue to promote the dehumanization of black girls and black women. 
assuming that a child has the capacity to think like an adult is asinine.  assuming that a broken child who has been exposed to sexual experiences could not grow up to be a broken woman is asinine.  blaming a child for not being able to protect themselves from predators in which their parents or guardians exposed them to or were unaware of is asinine. assuming that most women want to publicly disclose anything about their sexual history, especially something that will allow others to judge and berate them and then attempt to guesstimate their worth or value is ridiculous.

silence is not consent or approval.  and, we have the audacity to wonder why women wait such a long time to come out with their stories.. smh

text:
#metoo #metoomovement 
as a survivor please know this... it isn't easy to heal from. for the rest of your life you will have to live with the abuse and the remainder of what happened. 
but know this. you can still have a happy life. you don't have to let that make you a bad person. you don't have to be a victim all your life. i was a little girl when my innocent was taken. by people who i didn't know. in the foster care system people do a lot of stuff that gets overlooked. i've dealt with domestic violence.. something i live with on a daily basis.

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

there is a lot of different stuff that says " only two! " 
or " more then two!!" i feel we don't know enough to say which is which. because if you say " no this " another 12  things will just come out saying " no two!!" or " no more then two!!" so i feel its more complicated then a yes or  no answer. 
the human mind is so big and strange it  could do basically anything if it wanted  but also completely mess you up real bad. 
i know theres two sexes but i think there are more then two genders. 
to say there's only man and woman doesn't make much sense to me because what makes a man? what makes a woman gender wise not sex wise so is it just saying " i feel like a man/woman!" so why can't it be that way for those who are on the trans spectrum? 
to me two gender identities don't make sense when people have talked about feeling so many different things sincerely from their hearts. ~ witchy

text:
you are reckless, selfish, stubborn sometimes rude.
you've bottled up the pain of so much that has been done.
when you're hurt you close into yourself, shut down.
you love attention and yet love being by yourself more.
may god have mercy on your soul for you are truly lost.
daily you fight your demons yet no one knows of that which you endure.
you bear it alone, never speaking of it.
you can blame the broken home from which you came or the environment that you grew up in.
the people who tore you down so young.
you can point the finger at those who have whispered behind your back.
they all have played a role in your development.
but looking so deep into the past will keep you from moving forward.
you must love yourself more than these people claim they do.
look at where you stand now. ğŸŒ¹

text:
2/26 weeks of feminism. this week i asked @clairebresnan her thoughts on her meaning of feminism and why she needs it. 
she said this: â€œiâ€™m often afraid to draw attention to the ways gender inequality has impacted my life because i donâ€™t want to underscore my privilege or portray myself as a victim. however, i do see the ways societyâ€™s expectations of women have seeped into my relationships and self image. only once we acknowledge inequality can we address it. itâ€™s our responsibility to color in the grey space by normalizing and putting words to our shared experience. iâ€™m ready to replace â€œit could have been worseâ€ with â€œit shouldnâ€™t have happenedâ€ and recognize the ways iâ€™m affected. i wish i could refuse to walk the streets in fear, but a serial rapist has broken into my house. i wish i could trust fully, but my teammates and i were groomed as potential victims by my youth climbing coach and didnâ€™t see it until several people i care about were abused. i wish i could embrace my femininity, but when i do itâ€™s met with a marked increase in unwanted advances. i wish i could open up more to my male acquaintances, but itâ€™s always been portrayed as my responsibility to not lead people on or come across as needy. i need feminism because striving for a better world is not the same as complaining, and though my problems are small compared to much of the world, they should not be invisible.â€ #feminism #feminist #26weeksoffeminism #crankyfeminist #whatdoesfeminismmeantoyou #femme #timesup #metoo #weneedfeminism #patriarchysucksbecause #equality

text:
you can: make an effort even when you don't want to. .
you can: choose not to fight
.
you can:  not allow someone the opportunity to re-write your history .
you can: do nothing. .
having a disagreement with someone you love is hard. especially when you realize how wrong they really are and that they will never acknowledge that or give you any closure. .
so i sit with that.  and then move on, realizing my emotions and my moments are mine to define. .
as someone that is still coming to terms with the sexual abuse i endured as a child by a predatory neighbor....i have to constantly remind myself that it was not my fault. that there is no blame for 11 year old lacye. not telling and "allowing" it to happen does not make that my burden. or my crime. .
#survivornotvictim #whyididntreport #metoo #noblame #healing #trauma #tellingmystory #noshame #returningtoinnocence #hesguilty #karmaisreal #disagreements #hardship #survivor #tw #iamnotashamedanymore

text:
somatic practice short course, 2019
university of bedfordshire 
the somatic practice short course is aimed at dance practitioners, teachers, community dance artists and graduate level students.  the course explores contemporary issues in somatic practices with lots of opportunity to dance, explore and engage in experiential enquiry of the body mind. Â£60/Â£50 for part 1, 2, or 3. Â£140/Â£110 for parts 1, 2 and 3 booked together. 
booking: tamara.ashley@beds.ac.uk 
somatic practice short course part 1: contact improvisation and the somatics of touch
with tamara ashley

this course runs on wednesdays from 10-1 from 20 february to 27 march.

somatic practices offer a range of tactile tools that can enhance our practice of contact improvisation. touch and tactile learning can offer intuitive, felt and sensitive facets to our dancing. hands on work, and tactile tools can enable dancers to access different systems, alignments and feeling states in the body mind.  in this part of the course, there will be specific focus on touch and facilitation techniques.

in the context of consent, trauma, participatory questions and #metoo, we will look at systematic ways of approaching touch in terms of pedagogy, permission and performance.  personal somatic inquiry will be supported and encouraged through discussion, writing, journaling and reflection. 
we will explore touch and tactile dimensions of our dancing through dancing, watching and assisting one another. there will be lots of dancing! 
somatic practice short course part 2: contact improvisation and the art of relating
with anna jussilainen 
30 april â€“ 4 may 
an in depth investigation of the art of touch in contact improvisation.  #somatics #dance #touch #contactimprovisation

text:
good morning my beautiful kings and queens

one thing i can factually say is sexual abuse doesnt have a name, a race, a certain job, a sex, etc. it attacks anyone at anytime. look at him. you would never know by his business attire and handsomness. 
meet my king cortland jones who was sexual assaulted by a family member at the tender age of 4. i need you to understand how someones life is stripped away from them by someone elses choice. how do you expect someone to grow up and be normal?

courtlands journey wasnt easy until he met god. 
please welcome and give cortland some words of love and growth as he continues on his journey to happiness. his book, "out of darkness" shares how he is overcoming his abuse. 
cortland, my king, thank you for your bravery. sharing your truth to the world is a huge step towards healing and i commend you. i love you and stay on your journey. we are in this together. 
men hurt too. open your eyes people. this is real

dont be afraid to share your truth. free yourself from this darkness my kings and queens 
i love you and remember stay beautiful
#thebeautifulmovement
#sexualabuse#abuse#sex#movement#king#queen#advocate#journey#family#hurt#abuse#metoo#iloveyou#hurtpeoplehurtpeople

text:
"panty portrait: twat" from the panty project,12 of 51
.

fiber art, archival pigment print on museum cotton rag, 19 x 14 inches .
the panty project is an ongoing social practice project. participants, womxn and those who identify as womxn, courageously share with me their stories of experienced gendered transgressions and violent aggressions, whether cultural and/or interpersonal. participants write a word or phrase onto the panel of their selected undergarment; i hand-embroider over their mark-making and photograph them as if they have been taken off. this work addresses the inherent misogyny within our language, and the consequential "essestializing" of womxn, which reduces womxn, and those who identify as womxn, to "less than." this work is about healing and transcendence. 
womxn's long-silenced voices must be heard.
.

text:
this was a very hard poem to write because it evoked too many emotions. special thanks to @gurjot.s.kaler -  full video is out now. plz watch and share the link below.ğŸ‘ https://youtu.be/ffndfsmmrve ğŸ™

the poem, this  happens  with  every  girl : "me - too'' by gurjot s. kaler ,
is a heartfelt tribute to the millions of women in the world who suffer in  silence and are a victim of sexual harassment-cum-exploitation at every stage of their lives. indeed, it is actually a heartrending reality and a matter of grave concern to note that everyday,  innumerable women are raped, molested, eve-teased and sexually assaulted across the globe. 
the tragic truth is that every women has undergone the pain of sexual violence and faced some sort of sexual abuse during their lifetime, either directly or indirectly. 
the question which really begs for an answer is that whenever any kind of sexual crime happens with women, why are we all silent as the members of society ? don't we all have any moral and social responsibility to stand upright and defend our women's honor, prestige and integrity ? 
why do we refuse to raise our voice ? are we also waiting for that one day when our own mothers, sisters, wives and daughters will come home after becoming victims of sexual harassment and say that, "this happened with me-too". do not suffer in silence. raise your voice before it is too late. the world suffers a lot, not because of the violence of bad people but because of the silence of good people. be the change you wish to see in the world. 
the time has come to realize that we must gather the required courage to support, respect and protect our women as well as ensure their safety, security and survival at any cost.  therefore, "me-too'' is not a mere hashtag, its a global movement in support of women and is meant to  inspire them to raise their suppressed voices against all sorts of injustice in society. 
respect her - support her - protect her.

https://www.facebook.com/gurjot.s.kaler

https://www.instagram.com/gurjot.s.kaler

#metoo #metoomovement #gurjotskaler #gurjotkaler #respectwomen #womenempowerment - #regrann

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
as humans we want to connect and relate to one another. when we are validated in our experience it can be the most healing and powerful thing. tell your truth, reach out to others and don't give up. your experiences can help others. tell your fears and experiences.
be brave. you are worthy.
the truth sets us free.
i see you, keep going, i believe in you.

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
i've lived for most of my adult life on intentional communities, where essential resources, dreams, and power are all shared, to some capacity, among a group of people.  during this time, but especially in the last five years, i often found myself in the role of creating organizational structures for self governance and decision making. .

to do this, i had to learn how to ask what peoples' feelings and behaviors revealed about how we structured ourselves as a group, and try to shift those structures to affect people's future behaviors.  it was like living inside a dynamic puzzle, with all the pieces and all the outcomes growing and changing over time. .

there are lots of changes that we made that i'm proud of; there were also lots of failures that still confound me.  but as i exit the ranch community, i find that those failures are becoming my biggest tools for learning.  not just the how or the why or the what, but the fact of it:  there were certain things i failed to change, despite every ounce of my most tenacious efforts.  why? .

the podcast on being with rebecca traister and avi klein--#metoo through a solutions lense, hit me hard yesterday, because i think it speaks to a lot of the central issues we faced as a community, and to many of the reasons why our issues with gender inequality were so hard to change.  it was so emotionally challenging to dismantle structures of gender inequality from within relationships that were of paramount importance to all of us.  we learned how to talk about it, but not how to do it.  and this underlying reality was revealed in the patterns of behavior that repeated themselves over and over again, despite all our best words to the contrary.  i think this podcast is spot on in exploring the nature of the emotional challenges men and women face as we push for real vs performative feminism, and also some incredible perspectives for overcoming those challenges.

text: i am so inspired by everyone's comments, messages, and stories. when i first started talking to people about starting this business, they worried that i'd be dragged down or emotionally drained by others' stories. nope, quite the opposite. yes, i have sympathy and empathy for you because i've been there and i am still putting in the work every single day, but i can tell you with full confidence that i am not disheartened, mad, or saddened by any of the things your share. i have faith, love, and confidence in your growth potential. i know you can transform the suckiest part of your journey into your biggest strength. i believe in every single person that has seen the darkness and continues to put one foot in front of the other and i also believe in the good in humanity for those that are on here to learn how to support someone through their trauma. thank you for sharing your stories with me. let's continue to grow together!

i was 9 when i first met him, i was really happy to be honest because my previous molvi was too strict and he used to hit me for my mistakes. he was nicer and better at teaching me the quran, and i wouldnâ€™t have imagined in my worst of dreams he could turn out this way.
the first few days, maybe months were good, he was a nice person, at least that what my 9 year old self thought, he used to make jokes too aside from teaching me maybe which is why we bonded in a way, i was a child, i didnâ€™t know what was right or wrong. but as months passed, he started touching me in places i didnâ€™t feel nice. he used to keep his hand too high on my thigh when i used to recite the quran to him, he used to make me sit on his lap, and i didnâ€™t know how to ask him to stop. i was too silent. i didnâ€™t know what it meant or what it was.Â 
7 years, he went on for 7 years everyday touching me inappropriately and i couldnâ€™t stop it, i kept shut, it still haunts me and scares me. and the irony of him having two girls, i donâ€™t wish bad on that at all, never can, i would never want any girl going through this but oh god if only he thought about his little girls before doing this to me.Â 
i still shiver and cry whenever i think of it, i wish i couldâ€™ve stopped it some way but i used to go numb and silent. why is it that he who taught me islam and the words of god turned worse than a devil.Â 
i still havenâ€™t opened up to my parents about it, i donâ€™t know how to. it wasnâ€™t long back when i realized what was happening to me but i was too ashamed, i guess. and now it only cuts deeper every time i think of it.
i do see him sometimes, very rarely. but i prefer hiding myself somewhere instead.Â 
i cant face him anymore. the memories just open up in front of me like an open book and i see everything flash by. i donâ€™t think i can ever heal over this. i just cant.

â€¢

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
announcement

we have teamed up with a small states owned enterprise to produce a limited run of chop sticks with our little tiny tadpole sized big beautiful cranes (#bbc) sprayed all over from the tip and running down the shaft all the way to where the hand grips it firmly.

these limited edition chop sticks could also be used to hold up your man bun and yes they come in pink too. 
so the deal is we are now brand ambassadors for georgia chop stick, thus a 10% percent from each set sold with our offer code #longshaftbbc10 will go straight to environmental remediation in china particularly in heavy crane density zones.

there are only 100,000 sets made and they are strictly available in kitchen stores worldwide as as well as online and oriental grocery stores. this agreement could raise up to 1,200 yuan for the cranes. its not much but we will take anything for the cranes! go out there and #creaseforpeace bird lovers!

#fighttheman #metoo #endtheextinction #earthtoo #cranestoo #lgbqtc @peta @seashepherd #christmas #origami #vegetablepower #vegetable #vegancat #veganleopard #flatearth #spheroidalearth #deliciousvegfood #vegetablepowered #armtheanimals #getsomeporkbetweenyoursticks #crueltyfree #greenhousegas #climatechange #migratefortheclimate #chopstick #chopsuey #tofustirfry #collaborate #childlaborfree

text:
this is my dog, kratos. i rescued him from a life of abuse when he was 6 months old but he recused me everytime i faced abuse of my own. there were times i was so depressed i didn't want to live and feel pain anymore but my dog saved me from myself. if i was gone, who would take care of my baby? he gave me a reason to stay. that's why i wanted to create this foundation because animals have a way of helping us heal, and in return, we can help them heal as well. that's why i want to create a dv shelter that accepts animals because you need your biggest support in your biggest time of needğŸ’œğŸ¾
.
.
.

text: imagine that you are a rape victim. maybe you once sent drunken texts to a friend about your favourite sexual positions or exchanged nude photos with a previous boyfriend. if itâ€™s on your mobile, the police will look at it. if they think thereâ€™s a remote chance that it might be relevant, they will have to show it to prosecutors and disclose it to the defence â€“ and thereâ€™s every chance you will be questioned about it in court. the survivor knows that you or society blames her for the abuse, s/he will not feel safe or comfortable coming forward and talking to you. victim-blaming attitudes also reinforce what the abuser has been saying all along; that it is the victimâ€™s fault this is happening. it is not the victimâ€™s fault or responsibility to fix the situation; it is the abuserâ€™s choice. by engaging in victim-blaming attitudes, society allows the abuser to perpetrate relationship abuse or sexual assault while avoiding accountability for his/her actions.... #rapevictim #rapist #rape #hearmetoo #consent #abuse #metoo #womanempowerment #humanrights #feminism #survivingrkelly #sexualabuse #sexualviolence #sexualassault #rapevictim #rapeculture #feminist #love #anime #women #sex #domesticviolence #woman #nomore #survivor

text:
[1/5] â€œas 2018 has ended i have had a moment to reflect, i look back and see this past year as one of major ups and downs. running your own business is hard work - it requires commitment, grit, and resilience. not only am i carrying the weight of continuing to make it on my own, but i also have scars from a traumatic childhood that i have to breathe around every single day. in early 2017, i saw the #metoo movement gain momentum around me as many women came out and spoke about their experiences with sexual assault. it was then when one of my deepest truths, the fact that i had been molested as a child by a relative, started to be relived within the walls of my mind. i remember thinking to myself, â€œyou can actually speak about this?â€ i come from a community of south asian immigrants that abides by a â€œsweep under the f*ckin rugâ€ culture that made my speaking out more prolonged than it needed to be. i spent my childhood swallowed by my own silence and my inability to feel safe in telling anyone about my experience. the inspiration that the #metoo movement ignited in me let me know that my time to finally speak my truth was near and i collaborated with @browngirlmag and @sakhinyc to put together a panel of south asian women to share their stories of surviving sexual assault. the event took place in march of 2018 and was a success, i felt freer than i have ever felt before. being in a room full of other women who were fellow survivors gave me the sense of connection i was missing as a child. one of my goals in 2019 is to keep the trend of openness going with my friends and followers. the more i can share with you all about my experiences, the more i can impact lives and spark change around an issue that we have just skimmed the surface in talking about. recently, i stumbled upon a set of posts from @wendyslookbook that have pushed me to tell my story in more detail and to describe my journey as a survivor. drawing inspiration from wendy, i have come together with my team to create a narrative that best describes what i went through. this is my story, #metoo.â€ğŸ™ğŸ½

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
writing heals

when i started to write in my first journal i sincerely didn't think i'd get much out of it.. fast forward a decade and i have one of the most effective self-help tools for healing ğŸ““ğŸ™Œ it is such a great way to organise your thoughts, work through trauma and honestly express your feelings in a sincere,  non-judgemental way.

no-one else reads it so often you feel free to write things that you might never say or are too scared to say in real life! 
do something nice for yourself this weekend and buy yourself a new journal.. it can be the next step on your road to recovery!
.
.
.
.
.
.

text: in this past week ive grown tired of the collective sigh of outrage from black women whom are reacting to the rkelly docuseries. soooo... yep! i am saying it! in general, black women do not (initially) support other women who identify themselves as victims of harassment of men. period. instead, women of color would rather portray said victim as malevolent and vindictive and will go so far as to make enough statements against that woman who told her truth story, to ensure that not only is her #truth not a truth at all but that that particular â€˜victimâ€™ doesnâ€™t jibe with the manufactured version of the â€˜strong-black-womanâ€™ narrative. this conjured trace of us is designed to be held as an esteem for prominent women of our identity and socialization as the world should allegedly see it. we'd tear our sister down and puposely choke her with her hurt before we embrace her with empathy and hold her up as she goes through. ha! i speak from experience. btw, this is how rkelly was able to get away with the mess he is doing for so long. we've never, as a community, stood up for ourselves until the white man was involved and then we became outraged. sound familiar? #speakup #metoo #timesup #black #community #support #rkelly #surviving #hushnomore #tired #stop #enough #bgm #blackgirlmonologues #matter #justice #peace #mytruth #unapologetic #strength #tryme #movement #silence

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
how did i do it?

i created this simple system to keep focused on the future and wellness and sobriety 
the outside pentagon represents the five core pillars. i try to do them all everyday but the most important one is no drinking! 
the inside triangle represents mind body and spirit and i try to do something everyday for each of these to stay balanced. 
when i wanted a body transformation i did three things for my body everyday

when i wanted to pay off my debt i did three things for debt payoff everyday

when i wanted to get promoted i used it for my career goals and did three things for my promotion 
it's super flexible and keeps me on track! i don't attend meetings and rarely or never consider drinking anymore because this simple system keeps me so busy! it's hard to do all these everyday! 
it's free and anyone can do it any day at any age. i created it to help myself and my brother from relapsing and to create a healthy and wealthy life
#drydiet #sober #nohangover #noalcohol #metoo #transformation #empoweringwomen #nohangover #noalcohol #metoo #transformation #empoweringwomen #addictionrecovery #onedayatatime

text:
craig mclachlan, has been charged with assault and eight counts of indecent assault relating to events reaching back to 2014 â€” a potential breakthrough for the media companies he has sued for defamation, and for the countryâ€™s nascent #metoo movement.
.
.
.
mr. mclachlan, 53, has been charged for indecent acts said to have occurred in melbourne around the same time as his now-scrutinized performance in a stage version of â€œthe rocky horror show.â€ his interactions with women during that showâ€™s run at the comedy theater in melbourne were the subject of an investigative report from the sydney morning herald, the age, and abc, australiaâ€™s public broadcaster, revealing that several female co-stars accused him of indecent and inappropriate behavior.
.
.
.
the police declined to share specifics of the alleged assaults. however, legal experts said the charges threaten to undermine mr. mclachlanâ€™s defamation claim while highlighting the convoluted nature of australiaâ€™s legal system when it comes to sexual assault cases.
.
.
defamation law in australia strongly favors the plaintiff, and it is widely blamed for making it more difficult to confront the problem of sexual harassment.
the powerful men who end up accused tend to sue and the costs can be immense, not just to media companies but also to those who lodge the accusations.
.
.
.
mclachlan is currently suing fairfax media and abc, as well as an actress, christie whelan browne, for 6.5 million australian dollars, about $4.7 million, in damages. still, mclachlan now seems more vulnerable in part, media lawyers say, because the judge in  mclachlanâ€™s case has allowed for a rare defense of â€œcontextual truth.â€
.
.
.
4 days after the defamation trial begins on feb. 4, he is scheduled to appear in melbourne magistratesâ€™ court, to face 10 charges brought by the melbourne sexual offenses and child abuse investigation team: one charge of assault, eight charges of indecent assault, and one count of attempted indecent assault.
.
.

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnnâ€™s don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analyticaâ€™s parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from koganâ€™s app may not have been completely deleted. koganâ€™s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
let me drop this here 
____

in 2010, just before we had our first @walkagainstrape campaign, i approached one of my uncles (name witheld) for financial support, i went to his office and while i was pitching the whole idea and telling him why i truly want to lend my voice to silent victims of rape
___
he goes;
____ "esther before i write this cheque, if tomorrow you hear i sexually abused someone, perhaps something from my past,  will you take it up and prosecute me"? ____

me: yes sir, if  truly you committed the crime 
____

uncle: you will throw me under the bus even after i give you this money and support you
____

me: yes uncle
____

uncle: i guess we have nothing more to discuss then. tell my secretary to ask the next person to come in on your way out
____

me: thank you sir...
___

that was the last time he spoke to me, he  obviously blacklisted me. 
_____

i really needed the money  because it was the begining of a vision i was trying to sell to friends and family, corporate sponsors didn't want to identify with sexual violence  at the time, save for bro biodun caston-dada & lagos state min. of women affairs who threw their weight on the project.
____

back to my uncle....
____

for years i felt bad for not lying i won't stand up to him and just collect the money,  i remember my aunty that facilitated the meeting calling me "oponu ayerada" for not taking the money first! 
_____

i'm glad i didn't, i'm glad i took the walk when he subtly walked me out of his office.
____

i take out 8 years from my age now and i realised how young i was then, but i'm glad i didn't throw my integrity out of the door because of money!
_____

i'm not dropping this to say i am perfect but in light of the whole r.kelly issue and hearing his daughter speak her truth so boldly, i am glad i can stand tall and call him out if anyone comes forth with any sexual allegation (with evidence) against him without thinking of the blood tie or being rejected/ disowned.
___

i grew up with alot of rejection anyway so that's not a new thing to me...
_____

just saying i will stand by my truth than defend any sex offender.... family or friend!
____

never joke with your integrity

hannah barr, 27, a first-year ordinand and ph.d. student at wycliffe hall, oxford has been chosen to take part in the final of a new competition to find engaging young voices who think theologically about the contemporary world. she will deliver a talk on theology and #metoo.

the inaugural â€œtheology slamâ€, endorsed by the archbishop of canterbury, was open to anyone, lay or ordained, between the ages of 18 to 30. applicants were asked to write 500 words on one of 12 contemporary issues, which included theology and mental health; theology and the #metoo movement; and theology and artificial intelligence.

of nearly 75 entries received from male and female applicants, three women in their 20's  were chosen to take part in the final in east london on 7 march. each finalist will deliver a talk of 7-10 minutes.

thank you to all those who have supported me {and each of us} in our journey towards healing and restoration! itâ€™s not over!

text:
what are your opinions on abortions and birth control?
-
my opinion:
i personally am pro choice, and i don't really feel the need to push my opinions on abortion on others because we are free to believe what we want. as this post states, don't get an abortion if youre against them. if you think it's killing a human life, let the mothers who get abortions bare the pain of "murder". pro-choice people aren't forcing you to get an abortion, you can choose the carry if you want. do not force us to carry a child unwillingly if you're not willing to adopt or pay for check ups and hospital fees. the fact that many states are banning abortions just shows how much people only care about reproduction and not the quality of life.

text:
standing in solidarity for national human trafficking awareness day âœŠğŸ½
__
a hard subject for many to think about but the truth is, it's happening, right now, right where you live.  there are 40.3 million victims of human trafficking globally.  81% of them are trapped in forced labor.  25% of them are children.  75% of them are women and girls.  it's a billion dollar industry and right now, you might be thinking.. well what can i do?  the first thing is to educate your self.  you can watch a movie about it.  imagine yourself in that situation (it's the scariest thing) and how you pray that someone is on the other side fighting for you, looking for you.  be that person.  be the change.  education is the most important, then from there, comes the hope for change and then we become the change.

it's been 18 years since the night that wrecked me. it changed me forever. i thought it wasted me, but i won. i took it back. but a piece of me will always be missing. i'll always be a little broken. i'm lucky i've found a husband and village who will always love me anyway. broken or whole.

this year has been full of hills and valleys. the kavanaugh appointment wrecked me. i put on my sparkly headphones and braved the hearing. christine blasey ford and i are kindred. we are in a club together. and when one of my sisters is brave enough to tell her story, i will listen. i will ignore my anxiety. i will disregard my self-defense bubble and show up. i will always show the eff up when youâ€™re ready to tell your story. iâ€™m discouraged by the advancement of predators and bullies in our country, but iâ€™m encouraged by the helpers.

text:
i have been battling a lot of demons my whole life. i have suffered from depression since i was really young. i have tried to commit suicide 2 times, i used to cut myself and i have thought about taking my life more times than i can count. everyday is a battle. everyday i struggle to get myself up and get going. i ask myself why am i here... everyday? some days feel like absolute torture. i cry and i cant make the ones i love the most understand. i cant tell the ones i love how i feel. how do you explain the sorrow that feels so dead and cold inside you without them thinking your crazy? i'm not crazy... i'm lonely, sad, scared, afraid and full of anxiety. who do i have to talk to? where do i have to go? how can i fix myself when i cant afford to see someone? life shouldn't feel this way... i have 3 beautiful kids that are supposed to look up to their mother but i feel they are never going to understand.i have a wonderful man who has been with me on my roller coaster who i am afraid i am going to drive away one day because he cant get me... he cant fix me. i have god... he listens to me cry, scream, plead, beg and pray to just get me through the day. he helps me smile when all i really want to do is tell f it all. he is in my corner. his love never fails me. 
#depressionisreal #depression #godislove #suicide #suicideprevention #hurting #ingoditrust #love #help #rant #mystory #metoo #youwillneverunderstand #noonecares #me #mylife #mystruggles #thedemonwithin

why punisheth the child for the crimes of the keeper of the vineyard?

@milano_alyssa who kicked off the #metoo movement ran the open session where women from neighbouring islands shared their brave stories of surviving domestic violence...& pretty much every women in the room had a story to tell.
emma is a do-er (my kinda person) & decided in the now, to commit to building a refuge in order to help these women & children.

.

text_retweet:
repost from @theconsciouskid using @repostregramapp - "for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning.
â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.

the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.â€ the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews

"for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning.
â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.

the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.â€ the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews

text:
what's next for me?

last year, during the 2017-2018 nba season when i had issues related to being a female sports reporter aka "a girl in the locker room" i would talk to #michaelbeasley ( @michael8easley ) and say, "it's a tough day mike" and he'd say something profound like "none of it matters. water on the back"

he's poetic like that. 
he's a man of few words but they be really important words, like african proverbs. at his first #knicksmediaday - and his last - he said he was "carmelo with the left hand" and the reporters laughed at him. he wasn't laughing or kidding. he didn't get many opportunities at first to prove it so we had a lot of downtime to chat. chatting with #michaelbeasley is like you talking to yourself. he doesn't say much but he's hearing every word.

i managed to get some actual interviews out of him before he started proving himself in the craziness that is the new york knicks my favorite nba team on the planet.

i've always been a delusional knicks fan. every year, i buy into the plan that this year, this player, this coach is gonna turn this shit around. it doesn't happen but none of us true #knicksfans care. it's the knicks. it's madison square garden. the mecca. win or lose, we good.

but last season was not good for me. it was the most stressful, most disgusting year i've ever had. the knicks replaced their longtime media guy w/ #dansabreen aka the asshole who was in charge of covering up  #sexualharassment of cbs boss #lesmoonves he was not about to let his track record of fixing #metoo messes end w/ me. so what a player rubbed his naked balls on my back. so what there's video and witnesses. he's a fixer for nba and i am a #blackwoman like the ones @chancetherapper refused to believe. who cares about #blackwomen ?

mike's gone now. he took his talents to play w/ #lebronjames and i haven't been back to cover a single game in 2018-2019 season. not sure if i will.

maybe it's time to take a trip to la and check out the new #lakers for sure it's time to lawyer up. this is gonna be harder than getting a 9-1-1 tape for a dead #blackactress named #kimporter but i'm not letting this go. neither case. - dc livers aka the fly on the wall ğŸ’”

text: .... i remember the day you walked in to jewett academy and we saw each other. you was like jody? i was like azriel?! trying to whisper cause i was in class. we were so hype that we were going to the same school, it was such a crazy coincidence. them bus rides in the morning were mad long... we had to hop on at the bus stop at like 5am, get took to the high school, then stay at the high school for like two hours till our bus driver started picking up the other kids. omg i remember that bus attendant that was giving us gum and your piece was at the bottom of the bag and it had like dirt on it and lint from her purse we was dyinggggg laughing. we just knew she had a crush on jordany too, steady asking him all the products he putting in his hair and stuff. i remember in history class you and clyde would pass me notes cause our teacher made me sit all the way in the front; i remember i had you decorate my planner cause my handwriting was ugly; idk why i still have it, but i do... i was so hesitant to watch the documentary. i was afraid even to see you or hear things about you, but i finished it tonight & had to make a post. even if one person sees or likes or shares i just feel like if i was ever your friend i would try to do something to bring you home and this was the first step i guess. azriel you are smart, talented, strong, loved, confident, funny, charismatic, outgoing and so many other words that wonâ€™t fit in this little caption. idk what else to say az, just come home. #muterkelly #supportazriel #blacklivesmatter #metoo #blackgirlslivesmatter #teamazriel

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the companyâ€™s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when youâ€™re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a personâ€™s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the â€œtraining setâ€ refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your â€œfeature setâ€: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, itâ€™s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data â€“ the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that youâ€™re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

text:
christopher wylie, the whistleblower who exposed the widespread misuse of data by his former employer, cambridge analytica, has revealed how the company â€œweaponisedâ€ the fashion industry in the run up to the 2016 us election, which he claims helped donald trump get elected.

speaking at the annual bof voices festival in oxfordshire, wylie revealed for the first time a matrix based on data collected by the firm which he claims can show how usersâ€™ preferences for particular brands on social media platforms â€“ facebook, in particular â€“ were then used to help target these same users with pro-trump messaging. he compared the misuse of fashion-based data as one of the campaignâ€™s lesser reported â€œweapons of mass destructionâ€. - they [cambridge analytica] looked at actual people. how they engaged with certain brands was put into a funnel and helped build the algorithms, wylie explained. - when you look at personality traits, music and fashion are the most informative [tools] for predicting someoneâ€™s personality. a userâ€™s predilection for a particular label gives, he said, a very clear indication of what reports often call â€œpopulist political signallingâ€. cambridge analytica, which wasÂ shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trumpâ€™s former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 â€“ including cultural preferences such as fashion and music â€“ to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
- she [rebekah mercer] loved me. she was like, oh we need more of your type on our side!

your type? - the gays. she loved the gays. so did steve [bannon]. he saw us as early adopters. he figured, if you can get the gays on board, everyone else will follow. itâ€™s why he was so into the whole milo [yiannopoulos] thing.

robert mercer was a pioneer in ai and machine translation. he helped invent algorithmic trading â€“ which replaced hedge fund managers with computer programs â€“ and he listened to wylieâ€™s pitch. it was for a new kind of political message-targeting based on an influential and groundbreaking 2014 paper researched at cambridgeâ€™s psychometrics centre, called: - computer-based personality judgments are more accurate than those made by humans. - in politics, the money man is usually the dumbest person in the room. whereas itâ€™s the opposite way around with mercer, says wylie. - he said very little, but he really listened. he wanted to understand the science. and he wanted proof that it worked.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian
